<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="509">
Diagnosis A medium-sized, yellow member of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33744" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole flavens Roger" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole flavens Roger" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="509" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavens">flavens</taxonomicName>
group; the major has shallow but well-developed antennal scrobes; rugoreticulation across all of the occiput; a small mesonotal convexity, and angulate lateral postpetiolar margins, as well as posteriorly directed propodeal spine and rugoreticulate humerus. Resembles 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181833" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole ademonia Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole ademonia Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="509" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ademonia">ademonia</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181920" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole peltastes Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole peltastes Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="509" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peltastes">peltastes</taxonomicName>
, but easily distinguished by many features of sculpturing, development of the scrobe, and presence in the major of the mesonotal convexity, as illustrated. Measurements (mm) Lectotype major: HW 0.84, HL 0.92, SL 0.44, EL 0.12, PW 0.44. Paralectotype minor: HW 0.44, HL 0.46, SL 0.42, EL 0.08, PW 0.30.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="509">color Major: appendages and gaster clear yellow, rest of body a slightly contrasting reddish yellow (&quot;orange&quot;). Minor: concolorous clear yellow.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="509">Range Sao Paulo, Brazil; Misiones (El Dorado) in extreme northeastern Argentina; and Cuzco Amazonico, near Maldonado, Madre de Dios, Peru.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="509">biology At Cuzco Amazonico, Stefan Cover and John E. Tobin collected four colonies, all in terra firme forest, nesting in small rotten sticks on the forest floor.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
